data.title: Alyson Stoner speaks on multiple eating disorders and rehab
data.meta_description: Alyson, 25, underwent and extreme body makeover with the help of YouTuber Michelle Khare. Alyson worked with Michelle and others to alter her workout and eating habits to improve her body.
data.text:
Alyson Stoner has opened up about the multiple eating disorders she battled while working in show business during an emotional clip showing the actress undergoing an 'extreme body makeover'.

The 25-year-old actress is known for her roles in popular films including Cheaper By the Dozen, Step Up and Camp Rock. Besides her acting chops, the star also became known for her talent on the dance floor after appearing in Missy Elliot's Work It music video.

But in an emotional video with YouTuber Michelle Khare, Alyson spoke about the realities of her many years in the spotlight and how it damaged her emotionally and physically.

'I started working in entertainment when I was six years old,' Alyson said.

Alyson landed roles like Cheaper By the Dozen at a young age. She went on to star in multiple Disney movies and TV series, helping her garner quick fame as a child star.

'Being In the public eye growing up brought a lot of criticism especially about my appearance,' the actress, who was hospitalized and then went to rehab at age 17 for treatment of three eating disorders, detailed.

'We strive to keep this illusion of unattainablilty. But behind the scenes, we’re hurting ourselves to reach that limit.

'I ended up going to rehab for three different eating disorders: anorexia, exercise bulimia and binge eating. I believe it was just a response to a chaotic and unpredictable environment.'

Alyson has since taken a step back from dance and other acting projects to focus on her wellbeing.

She joined Michelle on her YouTube channel for a video that documented her six-week health journey, showing the performer attempting to gain more muscle and eat healthier.

'I’m kind of nervous to do this transformation publicly because I’m used to offering a finished product, not being a work in progress,' Alyson said at the start of the journey.

The video showed her meeting with a nutritionist and personal trainer to discuss her goals for the next six weeks.

Because Alyson follows a plant-based diet, the experts had to work to curate diet and exercise that would help her gain muscle.

'I think it’s very easy to assume I either have access to a bunch of professionals because of my position in the industry, or it's easier because I have a smaller frame or I’m slender,' she said about seeking expert advice. 'The truth of the matter is I genuinely need help.'

A plan was necessary between herself, the nutritionist and the personal trainer to gain muscle back into Alyson's body and finds way for her to be active again.

'Between having a pretty severe eating disorder and dancing 40 hours a week for several years, it’s starting to be work to even walk up and down stairs,' Alyson said.

'Recently, I’ve dedicated so much time to other interests that I’ve had quite a sedentary lifestyle. It doesn’t mean my love for dance has changed, it’s just simply you can’t do everything. But, unfortunately, taking a step back from being active my body has gotten much tighter.'

After taking before pictures, Alyson's new journey started with a set workout schedule for each day and a meal plan.

The body makeover also focused on getting around eight hours of sleep each night to improve her energy levels.

'This past week started off really smoothing, almost too simply,' Alyson said during her first week. 'Like the habits were taking, the food tasted wonderful, the workouts were great. And then I learned that I would be getting measured, and the idea of progress started kicking in instead of just focusing on process.'

She continued: 'Last night I crashed, and not into my pillow, into a bowl of snacks. I felt a lot of shame really quickly. Normally a slip-up would take me out of the game for a while, but I’m learning how to shorten that recovery period.'

Although she slipped on her diet, Alyson decided to move on from the moment instead of punishing herself. She was able to do this with the help of meditation.

The weeks progressed into the makeover with Alyson feeling stronger as well as more confident about the positive body goals she was building for herself.

'Something that was difficult for me was to accept that I was going to need to let go of certain goals that I had because I was changing priorities, I was putting my health first,' Alyson said in an emotional confessional during the third week.

'Before I was like, “Will this help my career?" Now it’s like, “Are you jeopardizing your health to make this happen?"'

On a trip to Belize, the star even figured out how to workout to stay on track with her body makeover.

'It’s important to me to show myself that my commitments are worth keeping,' Alyson said. 'It would be very easy to just throw everything away this week. But when there’s a will there’s a way.'

The final week of the makeover increased intensity dramatically, with the star working out more than ever and using heavier weights. Her end results then showed she gained muscle during the six weeks and lost body fat.

'I’ve been trying to make these changes for so long,' Alyson said. 'The clarity and the peace and the joy that I have in my everyday life is such a dramatic difference and that doesn’t have to do with how big my bicep is, but this does help.'

Alyson has dramatically altered her life in recent years.

In a personal essay with Teen Vogue last year, the star revealed she was interested in 'men, women, and people who identify in other ways.'

She also adopted a minimalist lifestyle by selling her house and moving into a studio apartment where she shops at local farmer's markets and wears hand-me-down clothes.

The extreme body makeover was another step for Alyson to alter her life.
